text:
\begin{equation}\label{SRproblem} 
\left\{\begin{array}{l}
\text{(i) }\  \widehat{G* x_\text{est}}=\widehat{G* x} \quad\text{ on } [-\nu_c,\nu_c] \\
\text{(ii) }\  \widehat{x}_\text{est} \ \text{ is supported in } \ [-\nu_\text{hi}, \nu_\text{hi}]
\end{array}\right.
\end{equation}

nexttext:
where for $\nu\notin [-\nu_c,\nu_c]$ the fraction $\widehat{y}_\text{fit}(\nu) / \widehat{x}_\text{know}(\nu)$ 
only contains wavenumber information coming from the noise term (see figure~\ref{fitting}).  To explain 
our fitting method to the experimental data of Neon, in figure~\ref{fitting} we show a plot of the discrete 
cosine transform\footnote{Fourier and cosine transforms are equivalent in this case, here we use the 
latter because it has the advantage of letting us to work with real signals only.} of 
$\log |\widehat{y}_\text{fit}/\widehat{x}_\text{know}|=\log \widehat{G}$ for 
some of our Neon and NIST data on a particular interval. 
First starting at $\nu=0$ there is 
a noisy signal mounted on a smooth decreasing curve that after certain point $\nu_c$ can be regarded as 
pure noise. The point where the signal behavior changes becomes the estimated cutoff frequency  
 $\nu_c$. 



\begin{figure}[h!]
  \centering
    \includegraphics[scale=0.372]{Figure2.eps}
  \caption{Plot of wavenumber per unit distance $\nu$  vs. $\log|\widehat{y}_\text{fit}/\widehat{x}_\text{know}|$.
  At the cut off wavenumber $\nu_c$ the graph shows a change of behavior.}
  \label{fitting}
\end{figure}


Once $\nu_c$ is known, parameters $a$ and $B$ can be determine by linear regression for 
$\log(|\widehat{y}_\text{fit}/\widehat{x}_\text{know}|)$ on the interval $(0,\nu_c)$. 
To have a more robust estimation, the determination of $\nu_c$ and the linear regression is repeated on intervals around different peaks and then the reported values are given by their average value. As it will be seen in 
what remains, the proposed approach to estimate the parameters is effective and good enough for the current application. 



\section{Experiment}

The experimental arrangement employed to obtain the optogalvanic spectra is shown in figure \ref{Diagrama}. It consist of three main parts, the light source, the discharge and radiation interaction region, and the detection part. The discharges used in this work were created separately using Neon and Argon. 
The cathodes were made of cooper and we use a planar cathode configuration with a separation between electrodes of $7$ mm. The Argon and Neon used was research grade purity. The vaccum system was made using a Pfeiffer turbomolecular pump of $100$ l/s that allows us to reach a base pressure of $10^{-5}$ Torr and the pressure measurements were made using a MKS baratron manometer type $626$ and a Varian Eyesys mini-BA vacuum gauge. We use a DC power supply $HP6516$ with a voltage range of ($0-3000$) Volts.\\ 
To excitate the plasma we used an Ekspla Optical Parametric Oscillator (OPO) pumped by a Nd:YAG pulsed laser. For the optogalvanic effect measurements we collect the voltage variations in a balast resistor of $3.9$ KOhm and this voltage was amplified by a SR$280$ Standford Research Systems boxcar averager in order get the best signal to noise ratio. The power of the laser was measured using a Ophir pyroelectric sensor PE$10-$S in order to get power normalized data. These measurements were send to a National Instruments USB$-6009$ Data Acquisition System (DAQ) and collected in a computer using a LabView automatization program.
\begin{figure}[h!]
  \centering
    \includegraphics[scale=0.4]{Figure3.eps}
  \caption{Experimental arrangement. L:Plano-Convex lens f$=150$ mm, PE: Pyroelectric sensor, R: ballast resistor $3.9$ kOhms, HV: DC power supply, LT: laser trigger.}
  \label{Diagrama}
\end{figure}
The laser resolution in the visible range reported here was $0.1$ nm and its wavelength was changed in an automated way. For each wavelength we collected several voltage values  and the values reported here are an average of at least 20 of these. 


